export const HYDROGEN_MASTER_MARKDOWN = "## 0. Master Chapter Map\n\n1. Introduction and electronic structure  \n2. Position of hydrogen in the periodic table  \n3. Occurrence and abundance  \n4. Isotopes: protium, deuterium and tritium  \n5. Isotope effect and zero-point energy  \n6. Preparation of dihydrogen: laboratory and industrial methods  \n7. Physical and chemical properties of dihydrogen  \n8. Uses, storage and transport of hydrogen  \n9. Special forms: atomic, nascent and activated hydrogen  \n10. Ortho- and para-hydrogen  \n11. Hydrides: ionic, covalent, metallic, complex and intermediate  \n12. Hydrogen ion and hydrated proton  \n13. Hydrogen bonding  \n14. Water: structure, properties and reactions  \n15. Ice and anomalous behaviour of water  \n16. Hydrates and water of crystallisation  \n17. Hard and soft water  \n18. Removal of temporary and permanent hardness  \n19. Demineralisation by ion-exchange resins  \n20. Heavy water, D₂O  \n21. Hydrogen peroxide, H₂O₂: preparation, structure, properties, reactions and uses  \n22. Hydrogen as a fuel and hydrogen economy  \n23. JEE Advanced exceptions, traps and comparison tables  \n24. High-yield reaction bank and revision sheet  \n\n---\n\n# 1. Introduction and Electronic Structure\n\nHydrogen is the **first and lightest element** of the periodic table.\n\n- Atomic number, \\(Z = 1\\)\n- Ground-state electronic configuration: **1s¹**\n- Ordinary hydrogen atom contains one proton and one electron.\n- Protium, the most abundant isotope, contains **no neutron**.\n- Elemental hydrogen normally exists as the stable diatomic molecule **H₂**, called **dihydrogen**.\n\nHistorically, hydrogen was isolated and studied by **Henry Cavendish**, who described it as an inflammable gas. The name *hydrogen* (“water former”) was later introduced by Lavoisier.\n\n## 1.1 Three fundamental ways hydrogen can attain stability\n\nBecause H has one electron in the 1s orbital, it can participate in bonding in three broad ways:\n\n### A. Loss of one electron → H⁺\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H \\rightarrow H^+ + e^-}\n\\]\n\nH⁺ is simply a proton for protium.\n\nA free proton is extraordinarily small and has extremely high charge density and polarising power. Therefore, **free H⁺ does not normally exist in condensed phases**. It becomes solvated or chemically associated.\n\nIn water:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H^+ + H_2O \\rightarrow H_3O^+}\n\\]\n\nMore realistically, protonated water exists as larger hydrated clusters such as:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H^+(H_2O)_n}\n\\]\n\n### B. Gain of one electron → H⁻\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H + e^- \\rightarrow H^-}\n\\]\n\nThe hydride ion, H⁻, occurs in ionic hydrides of strongly electropositive metals, e.g. NaH, KH, CaH₂.\n\n### C. Sharing of electrons → covalent bond\n\nThis is the most common mode of bonding for hydrogen.\n\nExamples:\n\n- H₂\n- HCl\n- H₂O\n- NH₃\n- CH₄\n\n---\n\n# 2. Position of Hydrogen in the Periodic Table\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/01_periodic_position.svg)\n\n\nHydrogen has a **unique position** because it resembles more than one family but does not fit perfectly into any single group.\n\n## 2.1 Resemblance with Group 1: alkali metals\n\nHydrogen:\n\n\\[\n1s^1\n\\]\n\nAlkali metals:\n\n\\[\nns^1\n\\]\n\nSimilarities:\n\n- Both have one valence electron.\n- Both can show oxidation state \\(+1\\).\n- Both can combine with electronegative elements.\n- Both form halides, oxides and sulphur compounds.\n\nExamples:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{HCl,\\ H_2O,\\ H_2S}\n\\]\n\ncompared conceptually with:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{NaCl,\\ Na_2O,\\ Na_2S}\n\\]\n\n### Why hydrogen is not a normal alkali metal\n\n- Hydrogen has very high ionisation enthalpy.\n- It is a non-metal under ordinary conditions.\n- H⁺ is extraordinarily small and cannot exist freely in ordinary condensed media.\n- Hydrogen mainly forms covalent bonds, unlike strongly electropositive alkali metals.\n\nApproximate first ionisation enthalpies commonly used for comparison:\n\n- Li: about 520 kJ mol⁻¹\n- H: about 1312 kJ mol⁻¹\n- F: about 1680 kJ mol⁻¹\n\nThus, in ionisation behaviour H is much less electropositive than alkali metals.\n\n---\n\n## 2.2 Resemblance with Group 17: halogens\n\nHalogens have outer configuration:\n\n\\[\nns^2np^5\n\\]\n\nThey need one electron to attain noble-gas configuration.\n\nHydrogen also needs one electron to attain the He configuration:\n\n\\[\n1s^2\n\\]\n\nSimilarities:\n\n- Both are non-metals.\n- Both can gain one electron:\n  \\[\n  \\mathrm{H + e^- \\rightarrow H^-}\n  \\]\n- Both form diatomic molecules:\n  \\[\n  \\mathrm{H_2,\\ F_2,\\ Cl_2}\n  \\]\n- Both form many covalent compounds.\n- Both need one electron for a filled valence shell.\n\n### Why hydrogen is not a normal halogen\n\n- H⁻ is much less common than halide ions.\n- Hydrogen is much less electronegative and much less reactive than fluorine/chlorine in their elemental states.\n- Its valence shell contains only a 1s orbital, unlike the ns²np⁵ configuration of halogens.\n\n---\n\n## 2.3 Limited analogy with Group 14\n\nAn advanced structural analogy sometimes noted is that the first shell of hydrogen is **half-filled** with one electron in a capacity of two, while Group 14 atoms have a half-filled valence shell in the sense of four valence electrons out of an octet.\n\nThere are also formal similarities between H– and alkyl groups in some organometallic series, but this does **not** justify placing hydrogen in Group 14.\n\n---\n\n## 2.4 Final conclusion\n\nHydrogen shows similarities with both alkali metals and halogens, yet differs substantially from both. Therefore, it is best treated as a **unique element with a special position** in the periodic table.\n\n### JEE key line\n\n> Hydrogen is unique because it can form H⁺, H⁻ and covalent bonds, whereas its very high ionisation enthalpy, moderate electronegativity and extremely small proton distinguish it from both Group 1 and Group 17 elements.\n\n---\n\n# 3. Occurrence and Abundance\n\nHydrogen is the **most abundant element in the universe**.\n\nIt occurs:\n\n### Free state\nOnly in small amounts in Earth’s atmosphere because its very low molecular mass makes atmospheric retention difficult over geological timescales.\n\n### Combined state\nIt is extremely abundant in:\n\n- water\n- hydrocarbons\n- carbohydrates\n- proteins\n- petroleum\n- natural gas\n- coal\n- acids\n- bases\n- hydrides\n- living tissues\n\nHydrogen forms more compounds than any other element.\n\n\n---\n\n# 4. Isotopes of Hydrogen\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/02_isotopes.svg)\n\n\nHydrogen has three important isotopes.\n\n| Isotope | Symbol | Protons | Neutrons | Electrons | Nature |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|---:|---|\n| Protium | ¹H or H | 1 | 0 | 1 | Stable |\n| Deuterium | ²H or D | 1 | 1 | 1 | Stable |\n| Tritium | ³H or T | 1 | 2 | 1 | Radioactive |\n\n## 4.1 Protium\n\n- Most abundant isotope.\n- No neutron.\n- Ordinary hydrogen chemistry is dominated by protium.\n\n## 4.2 Deuterium\n\n- Also called **heavy hydrogen**.\n- Discovered/separated on a macroscopic scale by Harold Urey.\n- Natural abundance is small, roughly \\(0.015\\%\\) range in terrestrial hydrogen.\n- Forms:\n  - D₂\n  - D₂O\n  - HD\n  - deuterated organic/inorganic compounds\n\n## 4.3 Tritium\n\n- Radioactive isotope.\n- Emits low-energy beta particles.\n- Half-life is about **12.3 years**.\n- Occurs only in trace quantities naturally.\n- Can be produced in nuclear reactions, including irradiation of lithium-containing materials.\n\nA representative nuclear reaction is:\n\n\\[\n{}^6_3\\mathrm{Li}+{}^1_0\\mathrm{n}\n\\rightarrow {}^4_2\\mathrm{He}+{}^3_1\\mathrm{H}\n\\]\n\nUses include:\n\n- radioactive tracer studies\n- fusion research\n- labelled compounds\n\n---\n\n# 5. Isotopic Molecules and Isotope Effect\n\nBecause H, D and T can combine, several isotopic forms of dihydrogen are possible:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H_2,\\ D_2,\\ T_2,\\ HD,\\ HT,\\ DT}\n\\]\n\nThus, **six isotopic dihydrogen molecules** are possible.\n\nFor water, isotopic possibilities become still larger because oxygen also has multiple isotopes.\n\n---\n\n## 5.1 Why isotopes have similar chemical properties\n\nH, D and T have the same electronic configuration:\n\n\\[\n1s^1\n\\]\n\nChemical behaviour is primarily governed by electronic configuration, so their qualitative chemistry is similar.\n\n## 5.2 Why their reaction rates differ\n\nThe large relative difference in nuclear mass changes:\n\n- vibrational frequency\n- zero-point energy\n- bond dissociation energy\n- activation energy\n- diffusion rate\n- equilibrium isotope distribution\n\nTherefore:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{C-H}\n\\]\n\nbonds generally break more readily than corresponding:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{C-D}\n\\]\n\nbonds.\n\nThis is the **kinetic isotope effect**.\n\nA classic consequence:\n\n\\[\n\\text{reaction involving C–H cleavage is usually faster than the corresponding C–D reaction}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n# 6. Zero-Point Energy and Isotopic Bond Strength\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/03_zero_point_energy.svg)\n\n\nEven at absolute zero, a bonded molecule cannot have zero vibrational energy.\n\nThe minimum vibrational energy is called **zero-point energy (ZPE)**:\n\n\\[\nE_0=\\frac{1}{2}h\\nu\n\\]\n\nFor a diatomic oscillator:\n\n\\[\n\\nu \\propto \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{\\mu}}\n\\]\n\nwhere \\(\\mu\\) is reduced mass.\n\nSince D is heavier than H:\n\n\\[\n\\mu_{\\mathrm{D-D}} > \\mu_{\\mathrm{H-H}}\n\\]\n\ntherefore:\n\n\\[\n\\nu_{\\mathrm{D-D}} < \\nu_{\\mathrm{H-H}}\n\\]\n\nand:\n\n\\[\n\\text{ZPE(D–D)} < \\text{ZPE(H–H)}\n\\]\n\nBecause the lower zero-point level lies farther below the dissociation limit, the effective bond dissociation enthalpy of D₂ is greater than that of H₂.\n\nApproximate comparison:\n\n\\[\nD_0(\\mathrm{D-D}) > D_0(\\mathrm{H-H})\n\\]\n\nTypical textbook values:\n\n- H–H ≈ 435.9 kJ mol⁻¹\n- D–D ≈ 443 kJ mol⁻¹\n\n### Important consequence\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\mathrm{H-H\\ breaks\\ more\\ readily\\ than\\ D-D}}\n\\]\n\nTherefore protium compounds usually react faster than corresponding deuterium compounds when bond breaking to the isotope is rate-determining.\n\n---\n\n# 7. Preparation of Dihydrogen, H₂\n\n## 7.1 Laboratory preparation by metals and dilute acids\n\nA common method:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{Zn + 2HCl \\rightarrow ZnCl_2 + H_2\\uparrow}\n\\]\n\nor ionic form:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{Zn + 2H^+ \\rightarrow Zn^{2+}+H_2}\n\\]\n\nDilute acids are generally used.\n\n### Important caution\n\nStrong oxidising acids may not liberate H₂ in the usual way because they can oxidise hydrogen or the metal reaction products.\n\n---\n\n## 7.2 Reaction of amphoteric metals with alkali\n\n### Zinc\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{Zn+2NaOH \\rightarrow Na_2ZnO_2+H_2}\n\\]\n\nThe exact aqueous zincate formulation may also be represented using hydroxo complexes depending on conditions.\n\n### Aluminium\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2Al+2NaOH+6H_2O\n\\rightarrow 2Na[Al(OH)_4]+3H_2}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n## 7.3 Action of water on reactive metals\n\n### Very reactive metals\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2Na+2H_2O\\rightarrow2NaOH+H_2}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2K+2H_2O\\rightarrow2KOH+H_2}\n\\]\n\nThese reactions are highly exothermic.\n\n### Steam with less reactive metals\n\nFor iron at high temperature:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{3Fe+4H_2O(g)\\rightarrow Fe_3O_4+4H_2}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n## 7.4 Action of water on ionic hydrides\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{NaH+H_2O\\rightarrow NaOH+H_2}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{CaH_2+2H_2O\\rightarrow Ca(OH)_2+2H_2}\n\\]\n\nCalcium hydride is sometimes called **hydrolith** in older texts and has been used as a portable hydrogen source.\n\n---\n\n# 8. Industrial / Commercial Preparation of Hydrogen\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/14_steam_reforming_shift.svg)\n\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/04_industrial_hydrogen.svg)\n\n\n## 8.1 Electrolysis of water\n\nOverall:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2H_2O\\rightarrow2H_2+O_2}\n\\]\n\nIn alkaline solution:\n\nCathode:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2H_2O+2e^-\\rightarrow H_2+2OH^-}\n\\]\n\nAnode:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{4OH^-\\rightarrow O_2+2H_2O+4e^-}\n\\]\n\nHigh-purity hydrogen can be obtained electrolytically, though the economics depend strongly on electricity source and process conditions.\n\n---\n\n## 8.2 Chlor-alkali process: hydrogen as a by-product\n\nElectrolysis of brine gives:\n\nAt anode:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2Cl^-\\rightarrow Cl_2+2e^-}\n\\]\n\nAt cathode:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2H_2O+2e^-\\rightarrow H_2+2OH^-}\n\\]\n\nOverall:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2NaCl+2H_2O\\rightarrow2NaOH+Cl_2+H_2}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n## 8.3 Coal gasification / water-gas process\n\nSteam is passed over red-hot coke:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{C+H_2O(g)\\rightarrow CO+H_2}\n\\]\n\nThe mixture:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{CO+H_2}\n\\]\n\nis called **water gas**.\n\nBecause this mixture is used as a feedstock in synthesis, it is also related to **synthesis gas (syngas)**.\n\n---\n\n## 8.4 Water-gas shift reaction\n\nHydrogen yield is increased by converting CO with steam:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{CO+H_2O(g)\\rightarrow CO_2+H_2}\n\\]\n\nIndustrial catalysts and operating conditions vary; older textbook processes commonly mention iron oxide/chromium-containing catalysts.\n\nCO₂ is then removed by absorption/scrubbing.\n\n---\n\n## 8.5 Steam reforming of hydrocarbons\n\nMethane is an important feed:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{CH_4+H_2O\\rightarrow CO+3H_2}\n\\]\n\nfollowed by shift conversion:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{CO+H_2O\\rightarrow CO_2+H_2}\n\\]\n\nOverall, depending on process integration:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{CH_4+2H_2O\\rightarrow CO_2+4H_2}\n\\]\n\nNickel catalysts and high temperatures are classically used.\n\n---\n\n## 8.6 Lane process — advanced/historical industrial chemistry\n\nA cyclic iron/steam process may be represented by oxidation and regeneration steps.\n\nSteam oxidation:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{3Fe+4H_2O(g)\\rightarrow Fe_3O_4+4H_2}\n\\]\n\nThe oxide is then reduced back to iron using a reducing gas, allowing the cycle to continue.\n\nThis is more important historically and for advanced conceptual questions than for modern NCERT core study.\n\n---\n\n## 8.7 Cracking and refinery by-products\n\nHydrogen is also obtained during petroleum refining and cracking/reforming operations.\n\n---\n\n# 9. Purification, Storage and Transport of Hydrogen\n\nHydrogen can be handled as:\n\n- compressed gas\n- cryogenic liquid hydrogen\n- chemically bound hydrogen\n- hydrogen absorbed/adsorbed in suitable materials and metal hydrides\n\nCertain metals/alloys absorb large quantities of hydrogen.\n\nExamples commonly discussed:\n\n- Pd\n- Pt\n- La–Ni type alloys\n- Mg/MgH₂ systems\n- Ti-based hydride systems\n\n### Major storage challenge\n\nHydrogen has very high energy per unit mass but **low volumetric energy density as a gas**, so storage tanks can be heavy or require high pressure/cryogenic conditions.\n\n---\n\n# 10. Physical Properties of Dihydrogen\n\nH₂ is:\n\n- colourless\n- odourless\n- tasteless\n- non-toxic in itself but an asphyxiant if it displaces oxygen\n- very light\n- only slightly soluble in water\n- combustible\n- diatomic\n\nImportant data:\n\n- H–H bond length ≈ **74 pm**\n- H–H bond dissociation enthalpy ≈ **435.9 kJ mol⁻¹**\n- Boiling point ≈ **20 K**\n- Melting point ≈ **14 K**\n\nThe high H–H bond dissociation enthalpy is central to hydrogen chemistry.\n\n---\n\n# 11. Why H₂ Is Relatively Unreactive at Room Temperature\n\nMany reactions of H₂ are thermodynamically favourable but kinetically slow.\n\nThe reason is the strong:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H-H}\n\\]\n\nbond.\n\nBefore reaction, the molecule often needs to be dissociated or activated:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H_2\\rightarrow2H}\n\\]\n\nThis requires large activation energy.\n\nTherefore H₂ reactions often require:\n\n- heating\n- light\n- electric discharge\n- transition-metal catalysts\n- reactive surfaces\n\n### Core concept\n\n> Dihydrogen is often kinetically inert at room temperature, not universally thermodynamically inert.\n\n---\n\n# 12. Chemical Properties of Dihydrogen\n\n## 12.1 Reaction with oxygen\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2H_2+O_2\\rightarrow2H_2O}\n\\]\n\nHighly exothermic.\n\nMixtures of H₂ and O₂ can be explosive over appropriate composition ranges.\n\n---\n\n## 12.2 Reaction with halogens\n\nGeneral:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H_2+X_2\\rightarrow2HX}\n\\]\n\nReactivity varies strongly:\n\n- F₂: extremely rapid/violent\n- Cl₂: light accelerates the reaction\n- Br₂: requires heating\n- I₂: reversible and needs favourable conditions/catalyst\n\n---\n\n## 12.3 Reaction with nitrogen: Haber process\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{N_2+3H_2\\rightleftharpoons2NH_3}\n\\]\n\nIndustrial conditions use high pressure, elevated temperature and catalyst.\n\n---\n\n## 12.4 Reaction with metals\n\nElectropositive metals form hydrides:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2Na+H_2\\rightarrow2NaH}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{Ca+H_2\\rightarrow CaH_2}\n\\]\n\nTransition and f-block metals may form metallic/non-stoichiometric hydrides.\n\n---\n\n## 12.5 Reduction of metal oxides\n\nHydrogen reduces oxides of suitable less-reactive metals:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{CuO+H_2\\rightarrow Cu+H_2O}\n\\]\n\nIt is therefore used as a reducing atmosphere/reducing agent in selected metallurgical processes.\n\n---\n\n## 12.6 Hydrogenation of unsaturated compounds\n\nExample:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{RCH=CHR'+H_2\n\\overset{Ni/Pd/Pt}{\\longrightarrow}\nRCH_2CH_2R'}\n\\]\n\nHydrogenation of vegetable oils produces more saturated fats.\n\n---\n\n## 12.7 Manufacture of methanol\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{CO+2H_2\\rightarrow CH_3OH}\n\\]\n\nIndustrial catalysts are used.\n\n---\n\n## 12.8 Hydroformylation\n\nAn alkene reacts with CO and H₂ to form an aldehyde, which may be further hydrogenated to an alcohol.\n\nSimplified:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{RCH=CH_2+CO+H_2\\rightarrow RCH_2CH_2CHO}\n\\]\n\nthen:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{RCH_2CH_2CHO+H_2\\rightarrow RCH_2CH_2CH_2OH}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n# 13. Uses of Dihydrogen\n\nMajor textbook uses include:\n\n1. Manufacture of ammonia.\n2. Hydrogenation/hardening of vegetable oils.\n3. Manufacture of methanol and other bulk chemicals.\n4. Manufacture of metal hydrides.\n5. Preparation of HCl.\n6. Reduction of selected metal oxides.\n7. Atomic-hydrogen and oxy-hydrogen torches.\n8. Rocket propulsion/space applications.\n9. Fuel cells.\n10. Hydrogenation reactions in organic synthesis.\n11. Controlled reducing atmospheres in industry.\n\n---\n\n# 14. Special Forms of Hydrogen\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/15_atomic_hydrogen_torch.svg)\n\n\n## 14.1 Atomic hydrogen\n\nProduced by dissociation:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H_2\\rightarrow2H}\n\\]\n\nusing very high temperature, electric arc or energetic radiation.\n\nAtomic hydrogen is much more reactive than ordinary molecular H₂ because no H–H bond first needs to be broken.\n\nRecombination:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2H\\rightarrow H_2}\n\\]\n\nreleases a large amount of energy.\n\nThis principle is used in the **atomic hydrogen torch**, producing temperatures of roughly **4000 K** near the working surface.\n\n---\n\n## 14.2 Nascent hydrogen — historical exam terminology\n\nOlder texts describe “nascent hydrogen” as hydrogen generated *in situ* at the moment of formation, for example during metal–acid reactions, and assign it enhanced reducing power.\n\nModern interpretation is more careful: there is not a unique stable allotrope called nascent hydrogen. Enhanced reactivity can arise from:\n\n- adsorbed atomic hydrogen\n- reactive metal surfaces\n- electron-transfer processes\n- freshly generated reducing species\n\nFor JEE-style historical questions, remember the conventional idea, but chemically interpret it as **in-situ activated hydrogen species**.\n\n---\n\n## 14.3 Activated hydrogen\n\nOlder advanced notes use this term for unusually reactive hydrogen produced by electrical discharge or activation of H₂.\n\nTreat this as a descriptive/historical term rather than a distinct stable allotrope.\n\n---\n\n# 15. Ortho- and Para-Hydrogen\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/16_ortho_para_temperature_graph.svg)\n\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/05_ortho_para.svg)\n\n\nH₂ exhibits **nuclear-spin isomerism**.\n\nEach proton has nuclear spin.\n\n## 15.1 Ortho-hydrogen\n\nThe nuclear spins are parallel.\n\nConceptually:\n\n\\[\n\\uparrow \\quad \\uparrow\n\\]\n\n## 15.2 Para-hydrogen\n\nThe nuclear spins are antiparallel.\n\n\\[\n\\uparrow \\quad \\downarrow\n\\]\n\n## 15.3 Energy and temperature dependence\n\n- Para-hydrogen has lower energy.\n- At temperatures approaching 0 K, equilibrium hydrogen becomes almost entirely para form.\n- At high temperature, the limiting equilibrium composition approaches approximately:\n  - 75% ortho\n  - 25% para\n\nThus:\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\mathrm{ortho:para\\approx3:1}}\n\\]\n\nfor “normal” hydrogen at ordinary/high-temperature equilibrium.\n\n## 15.4 Why conversion is slow\n\nDirect interconversion requires a change in nuclear-spin state and is kinetically slow without catalysts.\n\nConversion is accelerated by:\n\n- activated charcoal\n- paramagnetic substances\n- Fe, Ni, Pt, W surfaces\n- O₂ and other paramagnetic species\n- atomic hydrogen\n- electric discharge\n- suitable low-temperature catalytic surfaces\n\n## 15.5 Preparation of para-hydrogen\n\nHydrogen is passed over activated charcoal at low temperature, traditionally near liquid-air temperatures.\n\n## 15.6 Physical-property differences\n\nOrtho and para forms differ in:\n\n- internal energy\n- heat capacity\n- thermal conductivity\n- boiling behaviour\n- spectral properties\n\n### JEE trap\n\nOrtho/para isomerism is a **nuclear-spin phenomenon**, not ordinary geometrical isomerism.\n\n---\n\n# 16. Hydrides — Overview\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/17_hydride_periodic_map.svg)\n\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/06_hydride_classification.svg)\n\n\nBinary compounds of hydrogen with other elements are called **hydrides**.\n\nMain classification:\n\n1. Ionic / saline / salt-like hydrides\n2. Covalent / molecular hydrides\n3. Metallic / non-stoichiometric hydrides\n\nFor advanced study also include:\n\n4. Complex hydrides\n5. Intermediate hydrides\n\n---\n\n# 17. Ionic / Saline Hydrides\n\nFormed mainly by highly electropositive s-block metals.\n\nExamples:\n\n- LiH\n- NaH\n- KH\n- RbH\n- CsH\n- CaH₂\n- SrH₂\n- BaH₂\n\nBeH₂ and MgH₂ show strong covalent/polymeric or intermediate character and should **not** be treated as typical simple saline hydrides.\n\n## 17.1 Nature\n\nContain:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{M^+H^-}\n\\]\n\nor:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{M^{2+}(H^-)_{2}}\n\\]\n\n## 17.2 Properties\n\n- crystalline solids\n- high melting character\n- non-volatile\n- stoichiometric\n- do not conduct in solid state\n- molten ionic hydrides conduct electricity\n- H₂ is liberated at the anode during electrolysis of hydride-containing melts\n- strong bases\n- strong reducing agents\n- react vigorously with protic substances/water\n\nAnodic process:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2H^-\\rightarrow H_2+2e^-}\n\\]\n\n## 17.3 Reaction with water\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{NaH+H_2O\\rightarrow NaOH+H_2}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{CaH_2+2H_2O\\rightarrow Ca(OH)_2+2H_2}\n\\]\n\n### Important concept\n\nH⁻ is such a strong base that it removes H⁺ from water:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H^-+H_2O\\rightarrow H_2+OH^-}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n# 18. Complex Hydrides\n\nImportant examples:\n\n- LiAlH₄\n- NaBH₄\n- LiBH₄\n\nRepresentative preparations:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{8LiH+Al_2Cl_6\\rightarrow2LiAlH_4+6LiCl}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2LiH+B_2H_6\\rightarrow2LiBH_4}\n\\]\n\nComplex hydrides are important reducing agents and hydrogen-rich compounds.\n\n---\n\n# 19. Covalent / Molecular Hydrides\n\nFormed mainly by p-block elements and some lighter s-block elements.\n\nExamples:\n\n- B₂H₆\n- CH₄\n- NH₃\n- H₂O\n- HF\n- SiH₄\n- PH₃\n- H₂S\n\nUsually:\n\n- discrete molecular species\n- volatile compared with ionic solids\n- poor electrical conductors in pure form\n\nThey are classified by electron count.\n\n---\n\n## 19.1 Electron-deficient hydrides\n\nHave insufficient electrons for conventional 2-centre–2-electron bonding throughout the structure.\n\nCommonly associated with Group 13.\n\nExamples:\n\n- BH₃, which dimerises to B₂H₆\n- B₂H₆\n- higher boranes\n- polymeric AlH₃\n\nCharacteristics:\n\n- Lewis acidic\n- often polymeric or multicentre bonded\n- may contain 3-centre–2-electron bonds\n\n### Diborane\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/07_diborane.svg)\n\n\nB₂H₆ contains:\n\n- terminal B–H bonds\n- bridging B–H–B bonds\n\nThe bridges are classic **3-centre–2-electron bonds**.\n\n---\n\n## 19.2 Electron-precise hydrides\n\nHave the exact number of electrons required for conventional Lewis bonding.\n\nTypical Group 14 hydrides:\n\n- CH₄\n- SiH₄\n- GeH₄\n- SnH₄\n\nSimple EH₄ species are tetrahedral.\n\nThey are not normally Lewis acidic/basic merely because of electron deficiency/excess.\n\n---\n\n## 19.3 Electron-rich hydrides\n\nContain lone pair(s) on the central atom.\n\nTypical groups 15, 16 and 17:\n\n- NH₃\n- H₂O\n- HF\n\nExamples of lone pairs:\n\n- NH₃: 1\n- H₂O: 2\n- HF: 3\n\nThey often act as Lewis bases.\n\nFor N, O and F hydrides, intermolecular hydrogen bonding causes unusually high boiling points.\n\n---\n\n# 20. Boiling-Point Anomalies of Covalent Hydrides\n\nWithin a group, boiling point often rises down the group as molar mass and dispersion forces increase.\n\nBut:\n\n- NH₃\n- H₂O\n- HF\n\nhave much higher boiling points than simple mass trends predict because of **hydrogen bonding**.\n\nExamples of anomalous first-member behaviour:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H_2O \\gg H_2S}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{HF \\gg HCl}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{NH_3 > PH_3\\ (relative\\ to\\ expected\\ mass\\ trend)}\n\\]\n\nThe Group 14 hydrides show a smoother trend because CH₄, SiH₄, GeH₄, SnH₄ do not form comparably strong classical intermolecular hydrogen bonds.\n\n---\n\n# 21. Metallic / Non-Stoichiometric Hydrides\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/18_metallic_interstitial_hydride.svg)\n\n\nFormed by many d-block and f-block metals.\n\nExamples:\n\n- TiHₓ\n- ZrHₓ\n- VHₓ\n- LaHₓ\n- PdHₓ\n\nTypical compositions are variable, e.g.:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{LaH_{2.87}}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{TiH_{1.5-1.8}}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{PdH_{0.6-0.8}}\n\\]\n\nHence the law of constant composition is often not obeyed.\n\n## 21.1 Properties\n\nThey often:\n\n- retain metallic appearance\n- conduct heat/electricity\n- are hard\n- may become brittle due to absorbed hydrogen\n- show variable composition\n- can release H₂ on heating\n- act as hydrogen-storage media\n- can participate in catalytic hydrogenation\n\n## 21.2 “Interstitial” concept\n\nHistorically, H atoms were considered to occupy interstitial holes in an unchanged metal lattice.\n\nModern structural studies show the situation is more complex; many hydrides have structures different from the parent metal.\n\nTherefore “interstitial hydride” is useful but should not be interpreted too literally in every case.\n\n---\n\n# 22. Hydride Gap\n\nA common textbook trend:\n\nMetals in the middle of the d-block, especially Groups **7, 8 and 9**, show a marked tendency not to form simple stable hydrides under ordinary classification.\n\nThis region is called the **hydride gap**.\n\nImportant exception:\n\n- Cr in Group 6 forms CrH.\n\n### JEE warning\n\nDo not overgeneralise “no compounds at all.” Modern high-pressure/solid-state chemistry can be more complex. For exam classification, use the hydride-gap rule.\n\n---\n\n# 23. Intermediate Hydrides\n\nSome hydrides do not fit neatly into the three main classes.\n\nExamples:\n\n### BeH₂\n- polymeric\n- covalent\n- contains bridging H in chain/network descriptions\n\n### MgH₂\n- properties intermediate between ionic and covalent classifications\n\n### CuH, ZnH₂, CdH₂, HgH₂\n- may show behaviour intermediate between metallic and covalent/electron-deficient systems\n\nThese are useful JEE Advanced exceptions.\n\n---\n\n# 24. Hydrogen Ion, H⁺, and Hydrated Proton\n\nIonisation of gaseous hydrogen:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H(g)\\rightarrow H^+(g)+e^-}\n\\]\n\nrequires a very large ionisation enthalpy.\n\nTherefore isolated H⁺ formation is energetically expensive.\n\nIn aqueous solution, strong solvation stabilises the proton.\n\nSimplest representation:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H_3O^+}\n\\]\n\nbut proton hydration is better viewed as:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H^+(H_2O)_n}\n\\]\n\n### Why free H⁺ is absent in water\n\n- extremely small radius\n- extremely high charge density\n- enormous polarising ability\n- strong attraction toward electron pairs of water molecules\n\nThus, “H⁺(aq)” is shorthand for a hydrated proton.\n\n---\n\n# 25. Hydrogen Bonding\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/08_hydrogen_bonding.svg)\n\n\n## 25.1 Basic idea\n\nA hydrogen bond is an attractive interaction involving a hydrogen atom covalently bonded to an electronegative atom and another electron-rich site.\n\nFor classical JEE chemistry, the strongest familiar hydrogen bonding occurs when H is attached to:\n\n- F\n- O\n- N\n\nA broader modern definition includes a wider range of donor/acceptor combinations when there is evidence of bond-like interaction.\n\nGeneral representation:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{X-H\\cdots Y}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n## 25.2 Why hydrogen bonding is special\n\nHydrogen is very small. When attached to a highly electronegative atom:\n\n- the X–H bond becomes strongly polar\n- H bears substantial \\(\\delta^+\\)\n- a neighbouring lone pair can approach closely\n\nHydrogen bonds are weaker than normal covalent bonds but strong enough to produce major changes in physical properties.\n\n---\n\n## 25.3 Intermolecular hydrogen bonding\n\nOccurs between different molecules.\n\nExamples:\n\n- H₂O network\n- HF chains\n- NH₃ association\n- carboxylic-acid dimers\n\nConsequences:\n\n- higher boiling point\n- higher viscosity\n- greater enthalpy of vaporisation\n- molecular association\n- altered solubility\n\n---\n\n## 25.4 Intramolecular hydrogen bonding\n\nOccurs within the same molecule.\n\nClassic comparison:\n\n- o-nitrophenol: intramolecular H-bond possible\n- m- and p-nitrophenol: corresponding internal closure is not possible in the same way\n\nConsequences may include:\n\n- lower intermolecular association\n- altered boiling point\n- altered water solubility\n- changed acidity/basicity\n- conformational effects\n\n---\n\n## 25.5 Important hydrogen-bonded structures\n\n### HF\nCan form zig-zag chains:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{\\cdots H-F\\cdots H-F\\cdots}\n\\]\n\n### Formic acid\nCan form cyclic dimers through two hydrogen bonds.\n\n### Ice\nForms an extended three-dimensional hydrogen-bonded network.\n\n---\n\n# 26. Water, H₂O — Importance\n\nWater is one of the most chemically and biologically important substances.\n\nIt is:\n\n- a major component of living organisms\n- a universal reaction medium for many ionic processes\n- a major solvent in biological transport\n- central to climate moderation because of high heat capacity and high enthalpy of vaporisation\n\n---\n\n# 27. Physical Properties of Water\n\nWater is:\n\n- colourless in small quantities\n- tasteless and odourless when pure\n- highly polar\n- an excellent solvent for many ionic/polar substances\n\nIts unusual properties arise largely from extensive hydrogen bonding.\n\nCompared with analogous Group 16 hydrides, H₂O has unusually high:\n\n- melting/freezing point\n- boiling point\n- enthalpy of vaporisation\n- specific heat\n- surface tension\n\nIt also has a high dielectric constant, helping stabilise separated ions in solution.\n\n---\n\n# 28. Structure of Water\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/19_water_geometry.svg)\n\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/09_water_ice.svg)\n\n\n## 28.1 Gas phase\n\nWater is bent.\n\nApproximate values:\n\n- H–O–H angle ≈ **104.5°**\n- O–H bond length ≈ **95.7 pm**\n\nIt is strongly polar because:\n\n1. each O–H bond is polar\n2. the molecular geometry is bent\n3. bond dipoles do not cancel\n\n---\n\n## 28.2 Liquid phase\n\nWater molecules are associated through a dynamic hydrogen-bond network.\n\nHydrogen bonds continually break and reform.\n\nThe liquid is therefore less ordered than ice, but still strongly associated.\n\n---\n\n# 29. Structure of Ice\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/20_ice_3d_lattice.svg)\n\n\nAt ordinary pressure, common ice has an open hydrogen-bonded structure.\n\nEach oxygen is approximately tetrahedrally surrounded by four oxygen neighbours through a network in which a water molecule can:\n\n- donate two hydrogen bonds\n- accept two hydrogen bonds\n\nThe O···O separation in ordinary ice is about **276 pm**.\n\n## 29.1 Why ice is less dense than liquid water\n\nThe open hydrogen-bond network contains significant empty space.\n\nWhen ice melts:\n\n- some hydrogen bonds break\n- molecules can pack more closely\n\nThus:\n\n\\[\n\\rho_{\\mathrm{ice}}<\\rho_{\\mathrm{liquid\\ water}}\n\\]\n\nTherefore ice floats.\n\nThis also provides ecological insulation when lakes freeze from the top.\n\n---\n\n# 30. Anomalous Density of Water\n\nWater has maximum density near **4°C**.\n\nOn cooling from higher temperature:\n\n- normal thermal contraction increases density\n\nBelow about 4°C:\n\n- formation of a more open hydrogen-bond arrangement becomes increasingly important\n- volume increases\n- density decreases\n\nThis is why ice formation begins at the surface and floating ice can insulate water below.\n\n---\n\n# 31. Chemical Properties of Water\n\n## 31.1 Amphoteric nature\n\nWater can act as both an acid and a base.\n\n### With NH₃, water acts as acid\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{NH_3+H_2O\\rightleftharpoons NH_4^++OH^-}\n\\]\n\n### With H₂S, water acts as base\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H_2S+H_2O\\rightleftharpoons H_3O^++HS^-}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n## 31.2 Auto-protolysis\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2H_2O\\rightleftharpoons H_3O^++OH^-}\n\\]\n\nAt 25°C:\n\n\\[\nK_w=[\\mathrm{H_3O^+}][\\mathrm{OH^-}]\n\\approx1.0\\times10^{-14}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n## 31.3 Reaction with highly electropositive metals\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2Na+2H_2O\\rightarrow2NaOH+H_2}\n\\]\n\nWater is reduced to H₂.\n\n---\n\n## 31.4 Oxidation of water\n\nFluorine oxidises water:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2F_2+2H_2O\\rightarrow4HF+O_2}\n\\]\n\nIn ionic form:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2F_2+2H_2O\\rightarrow4H^++4F^-+O_2}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n## 31.5 Hydrolysis reactions\n\nExamples:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{P_4O_{10}+6H_2O\\rightarrow4H_3PO_4}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{SiCl_4+2H_2O\\rightarrow SiO_2+4HCl}\n\\]\n\nNitride hydrolysis:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{N^{3-}+3H_2O\\rightarrow NH_3+3OH^-}\n\\]\n\nA molecular example:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{Ca_3N_2+6H_2O\\rightarrow3Ca(OH)_2+2NH_3}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n# 32. Hydration vs Hydrolysis\n\n## Hydration\n\nWater molecules become associated with an ion/molecule without necessarily breaking the parent covalent framework.\n\nExample:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{Cu^{2+}+6H_2O\\rightarrow[Cu(H_2O)_6]^{2+}}\n\\]\n\n## Hydrolysis\n\nWater reacts chemically and cleaves or transforms bonds.\n\nExample:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{SiCl_4+2H_2O\\rightarrow SiO_2+4HCl}\n\\]\n\n### JEE trap\n\nHydration is **association/solvation**; hydrolysis is a **chemical reaction with water**.\n\n---\n\n# 33. Water in Hydrated Salts\n\nWater may occur in different structural roles.\n\n## 33.1 Coordinated water\n\nDirectly bonded to a metal ion.\n\nExample concept:\n\n\\[\n[\\mathrm{Cr(H_2O)_6}]^{3+}\n\\]\n\n## 33.2 Hydrogen-bonded water\n\nPresent outside the primary coordination sphere and connected through hydrogen bonding.\n\nFor CuSO₄·5H₂O, a common structural description is:\n\n\\[\n[\\mathrm{Cu(H_2O)_4}]SO_4\\cdot H_2O\n\\]\n\nThus:\n\n- 4 water molecules are coordinated\n- 1 is outside the coordination sphere and hydrogen-bonded\n\n## 33.3 Lattice/interstitial water\n\nOccupies lattice positions without direct primary coordination.\n\n## 33.4 Zeolitic water\n\nWater held in channels/cavities of porous aluminosilicate-type structures and often removable reversibly without complete framework collapse.\n\n## 33.5 Clathrate-type inclusion\n\nGuest molecules can be trapped in cage-like host water structures.\n\nThese categories represent additional structural forms of water found in solids and host–guest systems.\n\n---\n\n# 34. Hard and Soft Water\n\n## 34.1 Soft water\n\nProduces lather readily with soap.\n\n## 34.2 Hard water\n\nDoes not readily form lather because dissolved metal ions react with soap to form insoluble salts.\n\nMain responsible ions:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{Ca^{2+},\\ Mg^{2+}}\n\\]\n\nSoap reaction:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2C_{17}H_{35}COO^-+Ca^{2+}\n\\rightarrow (C_{17}H_{35}COO)_2Ca\\downarrow}\n\\]\n\nSimilarly for Mg²⁺.\n\nConsequences:\n\n- soap wastage\n- scum formation\n- scale formation in boilers/pipes\n- reduced heat-transfer efficiency\n\n---\n\n# 35. Temporary Hardness\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/10_hard_water.svg)\n\n\nCaused mainly by bicarbonates:\n\n- Ca(HCO₃)₂\n- Mg(HCO₃)₂\n\n## 35.1 Removal by boiling\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{Ca(HCO_3)_2\n\\overset{\\Delta}{\\longrightarrow}\nCaCO_3\\downarrow+CO_2+H_2O}\n\\]\n\nFor magnesium:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{Mg(HCO_3)_2\n\\overset{\\Delta}{\\longrightarrow}\nMg(OH)_2\\downarrow+2CO_2}\n\\]\n\nThe precipitates are removed by filtration.\n\n### JEE trap\n\nMagnesium bicarbonate gives **Mg(OH)₂**, not simply MgCO₃, under the conventional NCERT explanation because the relevant solubility equilibria favour hydroxide precipitation.\n\n---\n\n## 35.2 Clark’s method\n\nCalculated amount of slaked lime:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{Ca(OH)_2}\n\\]\n\nis added.\n\nFor calcium bicarbonate:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{Ca(HCO_3)_2+Ca(OH)_2\n\\rightarrow2CaCO_3\\downarrow+2H_2O}\n\\]\n\nFor magnesium bicarbonate:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{Mg(HCO_3)_2+2Ca(OH)_2\n\\rightarrow2CaCO_3\\downarrow+Mg(OH)_2\\downarrow+2H_2O}\n\\]\n\nCorrect dosage matters; excess lime can create treatment problems.\n\n---\n\n# 36. Permanent Hardness\n\nCaused mainly by soluble chlorides and sulphates of Ca²⁺ and Mg²⁺.\n\nExamples:\n\n- CaCl₂\n- MgCl₂\n- CaSO₄\n- MgSO₄\n\nIt is **not removed by simple boiling**.\n\n---\n\n# 37. Removal of Permanent Hardness\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/21_zeolite_column.svg)\n\n\n## 37.1 Washing soda method\n\nUse:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{Na_2CO_3}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{CaCl_2+Na_2CO_3\\rightarrow CaCO_3\\downarrow+2NaCl}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{MgSO_4+Na_2CO_3\\rightarrow MgCO_3\\downarrow+Na_2SO_4}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n## 37.2 Calgon method\n\nCalgon is sodium hexametaphosphate:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{Na_6P_6O_{18}}\n\\]\n\nIt complexes/sequesters Ca²⁺ and Mg²⁺ so they do not precipitate soap.\n\nThe ions remain bound in soluble complex form.\n\n---\n\n## 37.3 Zeolite / Permutit process\n\nA sodium zeolite may be represented schematically as Na₂Z.\n\nExchange:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{Na_2Z+Ca^{2+}\\rightarrow CaZ+2Na^+}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{Na_2Z+Mg^{2+}\\rightarrow MgZ+2Na^+}\n\\]\n\nRegeneration with brine:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{CaZ+2NaCl\\rightarrow Na_2Z+CaCl_2}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n# 38. Synthetic Ion-Exchange Resins and Demineralised Water\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/11_ion_exchange.svg)\n\n\nFor nearly complete removal of dissolved ions, water is passed successively through:\n\n1. cation-exchange resin in H⁺ form\n2. anion-exchange resin in OH⁻ form\n\n## 38.1 Cation exchanger\n\nSchematic:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2RH+Ca^{2+}\\rightarrow R_2Ca+2H^+}\n\\]\n\nIt removes cations such as:\n\n- Na⁺\n- Ca²⁺\n- Mg²⁺\n\n## 38.2 Anion exchanger\n\nRemoves:\n\n- Cl⁻\n- SO₄²⁻\n- HCO₃⁻\n- other anions\n\nand releases OH⁻.\n\nThen:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H^++OH^-\\rightarrow H_2O}\n\\]\n\nThis gives **deionised/demineralised water**.\n\n## 38.3 Regeneration\n\n- Cation resin: dilute acid\n- Anion resin: dilute alkali\n\n---\n\n# 39. Heavy Water, D₂O\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/22_d2o_comparison.svg)\n\n\nHeavy water contains deuterium instead of protium.\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{D_2O}\n\\]\n\n## 39.1 Preparation\n\nClassically by repeated/exhaustive electrolysis of water, exploiting isotope effects:\n\n- H-containing species are discharged/react somewhat more readily.\n- Residual water becomes progressively enriched in D₂O.\n\nModern industrial isotope separation can use additional exchange processes, but for NCERT the key method is electrolytic enrichment.\n\n---\n\n## 39.2 Physical differences from H₂O\n\nBecause D is heavier:\n\nD₂O generally has:\n\n- higher molar mass\n- higher melting point\n- slightly higher boiling point\n- higher density\n- lower auto-ionisation than ordinary water\n- slower reaction rates in many isotope-sensitive reactions\n\nTextbook comparison at around room temperature:\n\n\\[\nK_w(\\mathrm{H_2O})\\sim10^{-14}\n\\]\n\nwhile the analogous ionic product for D₂O is lower, of order \\(10^{-15}\\).\n\n---\n\n## 39.3 Chemical reactions\n\nD₂O undergoes reactions analogous to H₂O but forms deuterated products.\n\nExamples:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{SO_3+D_2O\\rightarrow D_2SO_4}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{P_4O_{10}+6D_2O\\rightarrow4D_3PO_4}\n\\]\n\nExchange:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{NaOH+D_2O\\rightleftharpoons NaOD+HDO}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n## 39.4 Uses\n\n- moderator in certain nuclear reactors\n- tracer/isotopic-labelling studies\n- reaction-mechanism studies\n- preparation of deuterated compounds\n\n---\n\n# 40. Hydrogen Peroxide, H₂O₂\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/12_h2o2.svg)\n\n\nHydrogen peroxide is an important peroxide in which oxygen has oxidation number:\n\n\\[\n-1\n\\]\n\nThis intermediate oxidation state explains why H₂O₂ can behave as both:\n\n- oxidising agent\n- reducing agent\n\n---\n\n# 41. Preparation of H₂O₂\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/24_anthraquinone_process.svg)\n\n\n## 41.1 From barium peroxide\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{BaO_2+H_2SO_4\\rightarrow BaSO_4\\downarrow+H_2O_2}\n\\]\n\nHydrated barium peroxide may also be used.\n\nPhosphoric acid can be advantageous in some laboratory variants because strong mineral-acid conditions can promote decomposition/contamination issues.\n\n---\n\n## 41.2 From peroxodisulphate\n\nElectrolytic oxidation of hydrogen sulphate/sulphate species produces peroxodisulphate:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2HSO_4^-\\rightarrow S_2O_8^{2-}+2H^++2e^-}\n\\]\n\nHydrolysis then gives H₂O₂.\n\nA simplified net hydrolysis idea:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{S_2O_8^{2-}+2H_2O\\rightarrow2SO_4^{2-}+H_2O_2+2H^+}\n\\]\n\nThis route is also useful conceptually for preparing deuterium peroxide using deuterated media.\n\n---\n\n## 41.3 Industrial anthraquinone process\n\nModern textbook industrial preparation uses cyclic oxidation/reduction of an alkyl anthraquinone/anthraquinol system.\n\nConceptually:\n\n1. alkyl anthraquinone is hydrogenated to anthraquinol\n2. anthraquinol is oxidised by air\n3. H₂O₂ is produced and the quinone is regenerated\n4. H₂O₂ is extracted and concentrated\n\nThe organic carrier is recycled.\n\n---\n\n# 42. Physical Properties of H₂O₂\n\nPure H₂O₂ is:\n\n- almost colourless / very pale blue\n- viscous\n- miscible with water\n- denser than water\n- capable of extensive hydrogen bonding\n\nCommercial solutions are commonly specified by concentration or **volume strength**.\n\n---\n\n# 43. Volume Strength of H₂O₂\n\nDecomposition:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2H_2O_2\\rightarrow2H_2O+O_2}\n\\]\n\n“x-volume H₂O₂” means:\n\n> 1 volume of solution liberates x volumes of O₂ at specified standard conditions.\n\nNCERT example:\n\n- 10-volume solution ≈ 3% H₂O₂\n- 100-volume solution ≈ 30% H₂O₂\n\nA common relation used in numerical problems near standard conditions is:\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\text{Volume strength}\\approx 11.2\\times M}\n\\]\n\nwhere \\(M\\) is molarity of H₂O₂, when the molar gas volume convention used is 22.4 L mol⁻¹.\n\nUsing 22.7 L mol⁻¹ gives a slightly different numerical factor. Always follow the convention stated in the problem.\n\n---\n\n# 44. Structure of H₂O₂\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/23_h2o2_dihedral.svg)\n\n\nH₂O₂ is **non-planar**.\n\nConnectivity:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H-O-O-H}\n\\]\n\nEach oxygen is approximately tetrahedrally electron-pair arranged.\n\nThe two O–H bonds lie in different planes, producing a skew/open-book structure.\n\nTypical textbook values:\n\n### Gas phase\n- dihedral angle ≈ 111.5°\n\n### Solid phase at low temperature\n- dihedral angle ≈ 90.2°\n\n### Critical correction\n\nH₂O₂ is **not a planar molecule**, and it possesses a non-zero dipole moment. Any scanned/OCR statement calling the molecule “non-polar” should not be used as the structural conclusion.\n\n---\n\n# 45. Decomposition of H₂O₂\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2H_2O_2\\rightarrow2H_2O+O_2}\n\\]\n\nDecomposition is accelerated by:\n\n- light\n- heat\n- dust\n- metal surfaces\n- transition-metal ions\n- MnO₂\n- alkali traces\n\nHence H₂O₂ is stored carefully.\n\n---\n\n# 46. Storage of H₂O₂\n\nStored:\n\n- in dark conditions\n- in suitable plastic or specially treated/wax-lined containers\n- away from dust and catalytic contaminants\n\nStabilisers may be added.\n\nReason:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2H_2O_2\\rightarrow2H_2O+O_2}\n\\]\n\ncan become strongly accelerated by catalysts/impurities.\n\n---\n\n# 47. Why H₂O₂ Acts as Both Oxidant and Reductant\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/25_h2o2_redox_map.svg)\n\n\nOxidation state of O in H₂O₂:\n\n\\[\n-1\n\\]\n\nOxygen can:\n\n### Be reduced\n\\[\n-1\\rightarrow-2\n\\]\n\nThen H₂O₂ acts as an **oxidising agent**.\n\n### Be oxidised\n\\[\n-1\\rightarrow0\n\\]\n\nThen H₂O₂ acts as a **reducing agent**.\n\n---\n\n# 48. Oxidising Action of H₂O₂\n\n## 48.1 Acidic medium: Fe²⁺ to Fe³⁺\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H_2O_2+2Fe^{2+}+2H^+\n\\rightarrow2Fe^{3+}+2H_2O}\n\\]\n\n## 48.2 Oxidation of PbS\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{PbS+4H_2O_2\\rightarrow PbSO_4+4H_2O}\n\\]\n\nBlack PbS is converted to white PbSO₄.\n\nThis is a useful qualitative demonstration.\n\n## 48.3 Sulphite to sulphate\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{SO_3^{2-}+H_2O_2\\rightarrow SO_4^{2-}+H_2O}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n# 49. Reducing Action of H₂O₂\n\n## 49.1 Acidic permanganate\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2MnO_4^-+5H_2O_2+6H^+\n\\rightarrow2Mn^{2+}+5O_2+8H_2O}\n\\]\n\nHere H₂O₂ is oxidised to O₂.\n\n## 49.2 Hypochlorous acid\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{HOCl+H_2O_2\\rightarrow HCl+H_2O+O_2}\n\\]\n\nEquivalent ionic formulations may be written depending on pH.\n\n---\n\n# 50. H₂O₂ in Basic Medium\n\nH₂O₂ also shows dual redox behaviour in alkaline medium.\n\nRepresentative reducing action toward permanganate:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2MnO_4^-+3H_2O_2\n\\rightarrow2MnO_2+3O_2+2OH^-+2H_2O}\n\\]\n\nRepresentative oxidation of suitable lower oxidation-state metal ions can also occur.\n\nFor exam problems, determine the role of H₂O₂ from the oxidation-state change of oxygen:\n\n- \\(-1\\to-2\\): oxidant\n- \\(-1\\to0\\): reductant\n\n---\n\n# 51. Tests / Characteristic Reactions of H₂O₂\n\n## 51.1 Iodide oxidation\n\nIn acidic conditions:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H_2O_2+2I^-+2H^+\\rightarrow I_2+2H_2O}\n\\]\n\nLiberated iodine can be detected by starch.\n\n## 51.2 PbS oxidation\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{PbS\\ (black)\\rightarrow PbSO_4\\ (white)}\n\\]\n\nwith H₂O₂.\n\n## 51.3 Permanganate decolourisation in acid\n\nAcidified KMnO₄ is reduced while H₂O₂ releases O₂.\n\n## 51.4 Peroxo chromium colour test — advanced\n\nUnder suitable acidic conditions, dichromate/Cr(VI) with H₂O₂ can form an intensely blue peroxo chromium species extractable into an organic solvent such as ether.\n\nThis is an advanced qualitative reaction; conditions matter because the blue species is unstable.\n\n---\n\n# 52. Bleaching Action of H₂O₂\n\nH₂O₂ oxidises coloured substances to colourless products.\n\nBecause decomposition produces water and oxygen, it is often called an **environmentally cleaner bleaching agent** compared with reagents that leave strongly coloured/toxic residues.\n\nUsed for bleaching:\n\n- textiles\n- paper pulp\n- hair\n- delicate materials\n- oils/fats in controlled industrial processes\n\n---\n\n# 53. Uses of H₂O₂\n\n- bleaching agent\n- mild disinfectant/antiseptic formulations at suitable low concentration\n- manufacture of perborates/percarbonates\n- environmental treatment of industrial/domestic effluents\n- oxidation of cyanide and other pollutants\n- chemical synthesis\n- pharmaceuticals and fine chemicals\n- laboratory oxidant/reductant\n- rocket/propulsion chemistry in specialised systems\n\n---\n\n# 54. Hydrogen as a Fuel\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/13_hydrogen_economy.svg)\n\n\nCombustion:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2H_2+O_2\\rightarrow2H_2O}\n\\]\n\nHydrogen releases a very large amount of energy **per unit mass**.\n\nA typical textbook value is roughly:\n\n\\[\n\\sim 142-143\\ \\mathrm{kJ\\,g^{-1}}\n\\]\n\nwhich is much higher per gram than common hydrocarbons.\n\n---\n\n# 55. Hydrogen Economy\n\n![](/notes/hydrogen/26_fuel_cell_storage.svg)\n\n\nThe **hydrogen economy** is the concept of using hydrogen as an energy carrier for:\n\n- storage\n- transport\n- conversion to electricity/heat\n- fuel-cell systems\n\n## Advantages\n\n- high gravimetric energy content\n- water is the principal product in ideal fuel-cell/combustion chemistry\n- can be made using multiple primary energy sources\n- useful for energy storage\n\n## Challenges\n\n- production energy/cost\n- low volumetric density\n- compression/liquefaction requirements\n- cryogenic storage around 20 K for liquid H₂\n- material embrittlement/permeation\n- tank mass\n- flammability and leak management\n- overall environmental benefit depends on how hydrogen is produced\n\n### JEE note\n\n“Hydrogen is pollution-free” is an oversimplification. At point of use, fuel cells can be very clean, while combustion in air can still generate NOₓ at high temperature. The total environmental impact depends on the production pathway.\n\n---\n\n# 56. Hydrogen Fuel Cells — Core Idea\n\nHydrogen fuel cells convert chemical energy directly into electrical energy.\n\nOverall:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2H_2+O_2\\rightarrow2H_2O}\n\\]\n\nAdvantages over combustion engines:\n\n- direct electrochemical conversion\n- high efficiency potential\n- low local pollutant emissions when pure H₂ is used\n- useful for stationary and transportation systems\n\n---\n\n# 57. JEE ADVANCED HIGH-YIELD EXCEPTIONS AND TRAPS\n\n## Trap 1 — H⁺ does not exist freely in water\n\nCorrect:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H_3O^+,\\ H^+(H_2O)_n}\n\\]\n\n“H⁺(aq)” is shorthand.\n\n---\n\n## Trap 2 — H₂ is not unreactive because reactions are always thermodynamically impossible\n\nIts low room-temperature reactivity is mainly **kinetic**, due to high H–H bond dissociation enthalpy and activation barrier.\n\n---\n\n## Trap 3 — D–D is stronger than H–H\n\nDue to lower zero-point energy:\n\n\\[\nD(\\mathrm{D-D})>D(\\mathrm{H-H})\n\\]\n\n---\n\n## Trap 4 — Ortho vs para\n\n- ortho: parallel nuclear spins\n- para: antiparallel nuclear spins\n- para lower energy\n- high-T limiting ortho:para ≈ 3:1\n\n---\n\n## Trap 5 — BeH₂ and MgH₂\n\nDo not blindly classify all Group 2 hydrides as ionic.\n\n- BeH₂: covalent/polymeric\n- MgH₂: substantial non-simple ionic/intermediate character\n- CaH₂, SrH₂, BaH₂: typical saline hydrides\n\n---\n\n## Trap 6 — Hydride gap\n\nKey rule:\n\n- Groups 7, 8, 9: do not form normal hydrides in this classification\n- Group 6: CrH is an exception\n\n---\n\n## Trap 7 — Metallic hydrides are often non-stoichiometric\n\nExamples:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{LaH_{2.87},\\ TiH_x,\\ PdH_x}\n\\]\n\nDo not expect simple integer composition.\n\n---\n\n## Trap 8 — Electron-deficient/precise/rich\n\n- Group 13 → deficient\n- Group 14 → precise\n- Groups 15–17 → rich\n\nClassic examples:\n\n- B₂H₆\n- CH₄\n- NH₃/H₂O/HF\n\n---\n\n## Trap 9 — NH₃, H₂O, HF boiling points\n\nAnomalously high because of hydrogen bonding.\n\n---\n\n## Trap 10 — Ice floats\n\nBecause open tetrahedral H-bond network makes ice less dense than liquid water.\n\n---\n\n## Trap 11 — Temporary hardness and magnesium\n\nOn boiling:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{Mg(HCO_3)_2\\rightarrow Mg(OH)_2\\downarrow+2CO_2}\n\\]\n\n\n\n---\n\n## Trap 12 — CuSO₄·5H₂O\n\nA common structural representation has:\n\n- 4 coordinated H₂O\n- 1 hydrogen-bonded/lattice-associated H₂O\n\n---\n\n## Trap 13 — H₂O₂ is non-planar\n\nGas phase dihedral angle ≈ 111.5°.\n\nDo not draw a completely planar H–O–O–H molecule.\n\n---\n\n## Trap 14 — H₂O₂ has O at –1 oxidation state\n\nTherefore it can act as:\n\n- oxidant\n- reductant\n\n---\n\n## Trap 15 — H₂O₂ storage\n\nLight, dust, metal surfaces and alkali traces can catalyse decomposition.\n\n---\n\n## Trap 16 — Hardness ≠ all dissolved salts\n\nIn standard school/JEE chemistry, hardness is mainly associated with Ca²⁺ and Mg²⁺ salts that interfere with soap.\n\n---\n\n# 58. Comparison Tables\n\n## 58.1 H, D and T\n\n| Property | H | D | T |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Mass number | 1 | 2 | 3 |\n| Neutrons | 0 | 1 | 2 |\n| Stability | Stable | Stable | Radioactive |\n| Relative reaction rate | Fastest generally | Slower | Isotope-dependent |\n| Bond to itself | H–H | D–D | T–T |\n| Bond dissociation trend | lower | higher | generally still affected by mass/ZPE |\n\n---\n\n## 58.2 H₂O vs D₂O\n\n| Property | H₂O | D₂O |\n|---|---|---|\n| Common name | Water | Heavy water |\n| Molar mass | ~18 | ~20 |\n| Density | Lower | Higher |\n| Melting point | Lower | Higher |\n| Boiling point | Slightly lower | Slightly higher |\n| Auto-ionisation | Greater | Lower |\n| Reaction rates involving O–H/O–D cleavage | Faster generally | Slower |\n| Nuclear use | ordinary coolant/solvent | moderator in suitable reactors |\n\n---\n\n## 58.3 Hydride classes\n\n| Type | Typical elements | Examples | Key feature |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Ionic/saline | electropositive s-block | NaH, CaH₂ | H⁻ present |\n| Covalent/molecular | p-block | CH₄, NH₃, H₂O, B₂H₆ | covalent bonding |\n| Metallic/non-stoichiometric | many d/f metals | TiHₓ, PdHₓ | variable composition |\n| Complex | metal + complex hydride anion | LiAlH₄, NaBH₄ | powerful reducing agents |\n| Intermediate | boundary cases | BeH₂, MgH₂, CuH | mixed character |\n\n---\n\n## 58.4 Covalent hydride electron classification\n\n| Class | Group tendency | Example | Behaviour |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Electron-deficient | 13 | B₂H₆ | Lewis acidic, multicentre |\n| Electron-precise | 14 | CH₄ | normal octet |\n| Electron-rich | 15–17 | NH₃, H₂O, HF | lone pairs; Lewis basic tendency |\n\n---\n\n## 58.5 Hardness of water\n\n| Type | Main cause | Removed by boiling? | Methods |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Temporary | Ca/Mg bicarbonates | Yes | boiling, Clark |\n| Permanent | Ca/Mg chlorides/sulphates | No | washing soda, Calgon, zeolite, resins |\n\n---\n\n# 59. High-Yield Reaction Bank\n\n### Hydrogen preparation\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{Zn+2HCl\\rightarrow ZnCl_2+H_2}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2Al+2NaOH+6H_2O\\rightarrow2Na[Al(OH)_4]+3H_2}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{CaH_2+2H_2O\\rightarrow Ca(OH)_2+2H_2}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{C+H_2O\\rightarrow CO+H_2}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{CO+H_2O\\rightarrow CO_2+H_2}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{CH_4+H_2O\\rightarrow CO+3H_2}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n### Hydrogen reactions\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2H_2+O_2\\rightarrow2H_2O}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H_2+Cl_2\\rightarrow2HCl}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{N_2+3H_2\\rightleftharpoons2NH_3}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{CuO+H_2\\rightarrow Cu+H_2O}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{CO+2H_2\\rightarrow CH_3OH}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n### Hydrides\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{NaH+H_2O\\rightarrow NaOH+H_2}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{CaH_2+2H_2O\\rightarrow Ca(OH)_2+2H_2}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{8LiH+Al_2Cl_6\\rightarrow2LiAlH_4+6LiCl}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n### Water\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2Na+2H_2O\\rightarrow2NaOH+H_2}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2F_2+2H_2O\\rightarrow4HF+O_2}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{SiCl_4+2H_2O\\rightarrow SiO_2+4HCl}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{Ca_3N_2+6H_2O\\rightarrow3Ca(OH)_2+2NH_3}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n### Temporary hardness\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{Ca(HCO_3)_2\\rightarrow CaCO_3\\downarrow+CO_2+H_2O}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{Mg(HCO_3)_2\\rightarrow Mg(OH)_2\\downarrow+2CO_2}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n### H₂O₂\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2H_2O_2\\rightarrow2H_2O+O_2}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{BaO_2+H_2SO_4\\rightarrow BaSO_4+H_2O_2}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{PbS+4H_2O_2\\rightarrow PbSO_4+4H_2O}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2MnO_4^-+5H_2O_2+6H^+\n\\rightarrow2Mn^{2+}+5O_2+8H_2O}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H_2O_2+2I^-+2H^+\\rightarrow I_2+2H_2O}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n# 60. NCERT MUST-NOT-MISS CHECKLIST\n\nA complete NCERT-oriented Hydrogen chapter must cover:\n\n- [x] position of hydrogen in periodic table\n- [x] occurrence\n- [x] isotopes\n- [x] preparation of H₂\n- [x] commercial production\n- [x] syngas\n- [x] coal gasification\n- [x] water-gas shift reaction\n- [x] physical and chemical properties of H₂\n- [x] uses of H₂\n- [x] ionic hydrides\n- [x] covalent hydrides\n- [x] electron-deficient, precise and rich hydrides\n- [x] metallic/non-stoichiometric hydrides\n- [x] water structure and properties\n- [x] structure of ice\n- [x] amphoteric nature of water\n- [x] hydrolysis\n- [x] hydration/hydrates\n- [x] hard and soft water\n- [x] temporary hardness\n- [x] permanent hardness\n- [x] Clark method\n- [x] washing soda\n- [x] Calgon\n- [x] zeolite\n- [x] synthetic ion-exchange resin\n- [x] demineralised water\n- [x] H₂O₂ preparation\n- [x] H₂O₂ structure\n- [x] H₂O₂ oxidising and reducing behaviour\n- [x] H₂O₂ storage and uses\n- [x] D₂O and uses\n- [x] hydrogen as fuel\n- [x] hydrogen economy\n\nAdvanced enrichment integrated:\n\n- [x] zero-point energy and isotope effect\n- [x] ortho/para hydrogen\n- [x] nuclear-spin conversion\n- [x] atomic hydrogen\n- [x] nascent/activated hydrogen terminology\n- [x] hydride gap\n- [x] intermediate hydrides\n- [x] complex hydrides\n- [x] deeper hydrogen-bonding effects\n- [x] isotopic exchange/deuteration\n- [x] tritium preparation/decay concepts\n- [x] advanced H₂O₂ tests and redox logic\n\n---\n\n\n# 61. Final One-Minute Revision\n\n- H: \\(1s^1\\), unique position.\n- Can form H⁺, H⁻, or covalent bonds.\n- H⁺ is never free in ordinary aqueous solution.\n- Isotopes: H, D, T; T radioactive.\n- D-bonds are generally stronger due to lower zero-point energy.\n- H–H BDE ≈ 436 kJ mol⁻¹ → kinetic inertness of H₂.\n- Industrial H₂: steam reforming + shift; electrolysis gives high-purity H₂.\n- Ortho H₂: parallel nuclear spins; para: antiparallel.\n- Para is lower energy; normal high-T ratio ≈ 3:1 ortho:para.\n- Hydrides: ionic, covalent, metallic.\n- Group 13 deficient; Group 14 precise; Groups 15–17 rich.\n- BeH₂ polymeric; MgH₂ atypical/intermediate.\n- Groups 7–9: textbook hydride gap.\n- H₂O bent, polar; ice open H-bond lattice.\n- Temporary hardness: bicarbonates; permanent: chlorides/sulphates.\n- H₂O₂ is non-planar and O is –1.\n- H₂O₂ acts as both oxidant and reductant.\n- D₂O: heavy water, moderator and isotopic reagent.\n- Hydrogen has high energy per mass but difficult storage by volume.\n\n---\n\n# 62. Complete NCERT Data Tables and Source-Restored Details\n\nThis section restores high-value numerical data and advanced details that were compressed too aggressively.\n\n## 62.1 Atomic and physical data of hydrogen isotopes\n\n| Property | Protium / H | Deuterium / D | Tritium / T |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| Atomic number | 1 | 1 | 1 |\n| Mass number | 1 | 2 | 3 |\n| Relative atomic mass | about 1.008 | about 2.014 | about 3.016 |\n| Protons | 1 | 1 | 1 |\n| Neutrons | 0 | 1 | 2 |\n| Electrons | 1 | 1 | 1 |\n| Electronic configuration | 1s¹ | 1s¹ | 1s¹ |\n| Molecular form | H₂ | D₂ | T₂ |\n| Natural abundance | ≈99.985% | ≈0.0156% | trace |\n| Stability | stable | stable | radioactive |\n| Melting point | 13.96 K | 18.73 K | about 20.6 K |\n| Boiling point | 20.39 K | 23.67 K | about 25 K |\n\nOther NCERT anchor values:\n\n- First ionisation enthalpy of H: about **1312 kJ mol⁻¹**\n- Electron-gain enthalpy of H: about **–73 kJ mol⁻¹**\n- Covalent radius of H: about **37 pm**\n- Hydride-ion radius, H⁻: about **208 pm**\n- H–H bond length: about **74.14 pm**\n- H–H bond dissociation enthalpy: about **435.88 kJ mol⁻¹**\n\n### Why isotope effects are exceptionally important for hydrogen\n\nThe percentage change in mass from H to D is enormous compared with most isotope pairs. Therefore hydrogen shows unusually strong isotope effects in vibrational frequency, zero-point energy, bond dissociation, diffusion, reaction rate and equilibrium isotope distribution.\n\nA standard kinetic example is that a reaction requiring C–H bond breaking is usually faster than the analogous C–D bond-breaking reaction.\n\n---\n\n# 63. Atomic, Nascent, Adsorbed and Occluded Hydrogen — Full JEE Treatment\n\n## 63.1 Atomic hydrogen\n\nAtomic hydrogen is generated by dissociation:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H_2 \\rightarrow 2H}\n\\]\n\nHigh temperature, low pressure, electric discharge or an electric arc can promote dissociation.\n\nIn the classical atomic-hydrogen torch, H₂ is passed through an electric arc. Recombination on the metal surface:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2H \\rightarrow H_2}\n\\]\n\nreleases a large amount of energy and produces a local temperature of roughly **4000 K**.\n\n## 63.2 Nascent hydrogen\n\n“Nascent hydrogen” is the historical name for hydrogen generated *in situ* at the instant of a chemical reaction.\n\nClassical examples include hydrogen produced during metal–acid reactions and reactions of amphoteric metals with strong alkali.\n\nModern interpretation: enhanced reducing action is better explained by adsorbed atomic hydrogen, reactive surfaces and coupled electron-transfer/proton-transfer processes rather than by a stable special allotrope.\n\n## 63.3 Adsorbed and occluded hydrogen\n\nHydrogen may be adsorbed on metal surfaces such as Pd, Pt, Ni and Fe. Historically, absorption/retention of gases by metals is called **occlusion**.\n\nSurface-bound hydrogen is central to catalytic hydrogenation.\n\nA useful classical qualitative order is:\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\text{atomic H} > \\text{nascent/in-situ activated H} > \\text{surface-adsorbed H}}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n# 64. Dihydrogen Reactions — Conditions and Important Details\n\n## 64.1 Combustion\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2H_2 + O_2 \\rightarrow 2H_2O}\n\\]\n\nHighly exothermic. Hydrogen burns but does not support combustion like oxygen.\n\n## 64.2 Halogens\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H_2 + X_2 \\rightarrow 2HX}\n\\]\n\nClassical reactivity order:\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\mathrm{F_2 > Cl_2 > Br_2 > I_2}}\n\\]\n\n- F₂: extremely rapid\n- Cl₂: accelerated by light\n- Br₂: requires heating\n- I₂: reversible and needs favourable conditions/catalyst\n\n## 64.3 Carbon and sulphur\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{C + 2H_2 \\rightarrow CH_4}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H_2 + S \\rightarrow H_2S}\n\\]\n\n## 64.4 Haber process\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{N_2 + 3H_2 \\rightleftharpoons 2NH_3}\n\\]\n\nUses elevated pressure, elevated temperature and an iron-based catalyst system.\n\n## 64.5 Methanol\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{CO + 2H_2 \\rightarrow CH_3OH}\n\\]\n\n## 64.6 Hydrogenation\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{C=C + H_2 \\xrightarrow{Ni/Pd/Pt} C-C}\n\\]\n\nUsed in oil hardening, organic synthesis and industrial reduction.\n\n---\n\n# 65. Ortho–Para Hydrogen — Complete Exam Notes\n\nHydrogen shows **nuclear-spin isomerism**.\n\n## Ortho-hydrogen\n\nParallel proton nuclear spins:\n\n\\[\n\\uparrow \\quad \\uparrow\n\\]\n\n## Para-hydrogen\n\nAntiparallel proton nuclear spins:\n\n\\[\n\\uparrow \\quad \\downarrow\n\\]\n\nPara-hydrogen is lower in energy.\n\nImportant equilibrium facts:\n\n- at very low temperature, para-H₂ predominates strongly\n- at high temperature, limiting composition approaches about 75% ortho and 25% para\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\mathrm{ortho:para \\approx 3:1}}\n\\]\n\nConversion is accelerated by activated charcoal, paramagnetic substances, O₂, Fe/Ni/Pt/W surfaces, atomic hydrogen, electric discharge and suitable low-temperature catalysts.\n\n---\n\n# 66. Hydrides — Expanded Classification and Exceptions\n\n## 66.1 Ionic/saline hydrides\n\nTypical: LiH, NaH, KH, RbH, CsH, CaH₂, SrH₂, BaH₂.\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H^- + H_2O \\rightarrow H_2 + OH^-}\n\\]\n\nExceptions:\n\n- BeH₂: polymeric/covalent\n- MgH₂: intermediate/non-simple ionic character\n\n## 66.2 Covalent hydrides\n\n### Electron-deficient\nGroup 13 tendency: BH₃, B₂H₆, higher boranes, AlH₃.\n\n### Electron-precise\nGroup 14: CH₄, SiH₄, GeH₄, SnH₄.\n\n### Electron-rich\nGroups 15–17: NH₃, H₂O, HF.\n\n## 66.3 Metallic/non-stoichiometric hydrides\n\nExamples: TiHₓ, ZrHₓ, VHₓ, LaHₓ, PdHₓ.\n\nTypical features: variable composition, metallic conductivity, lattice expansion, brittleness, hydrogen uptake and catalytic relevance.\n\nThe old term **interstitial hydride** is a useful model, but many real hydrides do not preserve the parent metal lattice unchanged.\n\n## 66.4 Hydride gap\n\nFor NCERT/JEE classification, Groups **7, 8 and 9** form the textbook hydride-gap region.\n\n## 66.5 Complex hydrides\n\nLiAlH₄, NaBH₄, LiBH₄.\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{8LiH + Al_2Cl_6 \\rightarrow 2LiAlH_4 + 6LiCl}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2LiH + B_2H_6 \\rightarrow 2LiBH_4}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n# 67. Hydrogen Bonding — Extended JEE Advanced Treatment\n\nHydrogen bonding affects boiling point, melting point, viscosity, association, solubility, acidity/basicity and molecular conformation.\n\n## 67.1 Intermolecular hydrogen bonding\n\nExamples: H₂O network, HF chains, NH₃ association, alcohols, carboxylic-acid dimers.\n\n## 67.2 Intramolecular hydrogen bonding\n\nExamples: o-nitrophenol, salicylaldehyde, salicylic acid and suitable β-dicarbonyl/enol systems.\n\nIt can reduce intermolecular association, lower water solubility, alter boiling behaviour and stabilise particular conformations.\n\n## 67.3 Advanced entropy insight\n\nHydrogen-bonded liquids can undergo unusually large structural reorganisation during vaporisation. HF is exceptional because association can persist in vapour as \\((HF)_n\\).\n\n---\n\n# 68. Water and Heavy Water — Full Numerical Comparison\n\n## 68.1 Water structural values\n\n- H–O–H angle: about **104.5°**\n- O–H bond length: about **95.7 pm**\n- O···O separation in ordinary ice: about **276 pm**\n\nWater has unusually high boiling point, melting point, heat capacity, heat of vaporisation, surface tension and dielectric constant because of hydrogen bonding.\n\n## 68.2 Estimated world water distribution — NCERT table\n\n| Source | Approx. % of total |\n|---|---:|\n| Oceans | 97.33 |\n| Polar ice and glaciers | 2.04 |\n| Ground water | 0.61 |\n| Lakes | 0.009 |\n| Saline lakes/inland seas | 0.008 |\n| Soil moisture | 0.005 |\n| Atmospheric water vapour | 0.001 |\n| Rivers | 0.0001 |\n\n## 68.3 H₂O vs D₂O\n\n| Property | H₂O | D₂O |\n|---|---:|---:|\n| Molar mass | ≈18.015 g mol⁻¹ | ≈20.028 g mol⁻¹ |\n| Melting point | ≈273.0 K | ≈276.8 K |\n| Boiling point | ≈373.0 K | ≈374.4 K |\n| Density | lower | higher |\n| Temperature of maximum density | ≈277 K | ≈284 K |\n| Auto-ionisation | higher | lower |\n| O–H/O–D cleavage rate | faster | slower |\n\nUses of D₂O: moderator in suitable reactors, isotopic tracer, mechanistic probe and preparation of deuterated compounds.\n\n---\n\n# 69. Hydrogen Peroxide — Complete Structural Data and Preparation Routes\n\n## 69.1 Structural data\n\nHydrogen peroxide is non-planar and polar.\n\nApproximate source values:\n\n- O–O bond length: about **147.5 pm**\n- O–H bond length: about **95–97 pm**\n- H–O–O bond angle: about **94–95°**\n- gas-phase dihedral angle: about **111.5°**\n- solid-phase dihedral angle: about **90.2°**\n- dipole moment: about **2.1 D**\n\n## 69.2 Laboratory preparation\n\n### From sodium peroxide\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{Na_2O_2 + H_2SO_4 \\rightarrow Na_2SO_4 + H_2O_2}\n\\]\n\nIce-cold dilute acid conditions minimise decomposition.\n\n### From hydrated barium peroxide\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{BaO_2\\cdot 8H_2O + H_2SO_4\n\\rightarrow BaSO_4\\downarrow + H_2O_2 + 8H_2O}\n\\]\n\nHydrated material is preferred because a BaSO₄ coating can passivate anhydrous BaO₂.\n\n### Peroxodisulphate route\n\nElectrolytic formation of peroxodisulphate followed by hydrolysis yields H₂O₂.\n\n### Anthraquinone process\n\n1. alkyl anthraquinone is hydrogenated\n2. anthraquinol is oxidised by air\n3. H₂O₂ is produced\n4. quinone carrier is regenerated\n5. H₂O₂ is extracted and concentrated\n\n## 69.3 Volume strength\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2H_2O_2 \\rightarrow 2H_2O + O_2}\n\\]\n\nUsing 22.4 L mol⁻¹ gas volume:\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\text{volume strength} \\approx 11.2\\times M}\n\\]\n\n## 69.4 Important tests\n\n- acidified KMnO₄ decolourisation with O₂ evolution\n- iodide oxidation to iodine\n- black PbS converted to white PbSO₄\n- blue peroxo-chromium species under suitable conditions\n\n---\n\n# 70. Final Source-Coverage Checklist\n\nThe rebuilt chapter explicitly covers complete NCERT backbone, isotope data, isotope effect, zero-point energy, all H₂ preparation routes, water gas/syngas/shift/reforming, atomic/nascent/adsorbed hydrogen, ortho/para hydrogen, full hydride classification, hydrogen bonding, water/ice, hydration/hydrolysis/hydrates, hard water and every softening method, D₂O, H₂O₂ full data/preparation/redox/tests, fuel cells, hydrogen economy, reaction bank and JEE traps.\n\n---\n\n# 71. Additional Handwritten + Advanced Inorganic Details\n\n## 71.1 Active hydrogen and “hyzone” terminology\n\nOlder advanced notes distinguish several activated forms of hydrogen.\n\n### Atomic hydrogen\nProduced by passing H₂ through a high-temperature electric arc:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H_2 \\rightarrow 2H}\n\\]\n\nAtomic hydrogen is extremely reactive because recombination to H₂ releases a large amount of energy.\n\n### Active hydrogen\nA stream of H₂ exposed to a silent electrical discharge at high voltage may form a highly reactive activated state.\n\nOlder literature sometimes used names such as **hyzone** or proposed transient excited/polyatomic hydrogen species. These names are historical and should not be confused with a stable allotrope of hydrogen.\n\n### Practical reactivity idea\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\text{atomic H} > \\text{nascent/in-situ activated H} > \\text{ordinary H_2}}\n\\]\n\nThe exact order depends on how the reactive hydrogen is generated and on the reacting surface.\n\n---\n\n## 71.2 Molecular hydrogen — kinetic inertness and catalysis\n\nHydrogen is thermodynamically capable of many reactions but is often **kinetically slow** at room temperature because the H–H bond is very strong.\n\n\\[\nD(\\mathrm{H-H}) \\approx 435.9\\ \\mathrm{kJ\\,mol^{-1}}\n\\]\n\nBreaking or strongly weakening this bond is often the rate-controlling step.\n\nTransition-metal catalysts help by:\n\n1. adsorbing H₂,\n2. weakening or dissociating the H–H bond,\n3. producing reactive surface hydrogen,\n4. lowering the activation barrier.\n\nExamples:\n\n- Haber process: activated Fe\n- hydrogenation: Ni, Pd, Pt\n- methanol synthesis: Cu/Zn-based catalysts\n\n---\n\n## 71.3 Oxy-hydrogen flame and explosive mixtures\n\nHydrogen burns in oxygen:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2H_2 + O_2 \\rightarrow 2H_2O}\n\\]\n\nAn oxy-hydrogen flame can reach temperatures close to **3000°C**.\n\nA near-stoichiometric mixture of H₂ and O₂, especially close to a **2:1 molar ratio**, is highly explosive on ignition.\n\n---\n\n## 71.4 Metallic hydrides — deeper structural behaviour\n\nTypical non-stoichiometric formulas include approximately:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{LaH_{2.87},\\ YbH_{2.55},\\ TiH_{1.8},\\ ZrH_{1.9},\\ VH_{1.6},\\ NbH_{0.7},\\ PdH_{0.7}}\n\\]\n\nThese are better viewed as hydrogen-containing metallic phases or solid solutions than as simple ionic compounds.\n\nImportant points:\n\n- composition can vary continuously\n- electrical conductivity often remains metallic\n- insertion of hydrogen can expand the lattice\n- metals may become brittle after absorbing hydrogen\n- absorbed hydrogen may participate in catalytic reduction/hydrogenation\n- hydrogen storage in Pd and related systems is reversible under suitable conditions\n\n### Titanium embrittlement idea\n\nHydrogen dissolved in titanium weakens the metal and makes it brittle. This is why titanium processing for high-strength applications avoids hydrogen-containing atmospheres.\n\n---\n\n## 71.5 Ionic hydrides — evidence for H⁻\n\nEvidence supporting ionic character includes:\n\n### Molten-state electrolysis\n\nMolten LiH conducts electricity and hydrogen is liberated at the anode, supporting the presence of H⁻.\n\nAnode process:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{2H^- \\rightarrow H_2 + 2e^-}\n\\]\n\n### Dissolution in molten salts\n\nSome ionic hydrides that decompose before melting can dissolve in fused alkali-halide mixtures and still show electrolytic behaviour characteristic of H⁻.\n\n### Crystal structure\n\nTheir crystal structures are non-directional and salt-like.\n\n### Reactivity trend\n\nGroup 1 hydrides are generally more reactive than corresponding Group 2 hydrides, and reactivity tends to increase down a group.\n\n---\n\n## 71.6 Hydrogen ion — energetic explanation\n\nThe ionisation enthalpy of H is very high:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H(g)\\rightarrow H^+(g)+e^-}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\Delta_iH \\approx 1311\\text{–}1312\\ \\mathrm{kJ\\,mol^{-1}}\n\\]\n\nTherefore, gaseous hydrogen compounds are normally covalent rather than containing free H⁺.\n\nIn water, the enormous hydration energy of the proton helps compensate this energy cost.\n\nHydrated forms include:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H_3O^+}\n\\]\n\nand larger protonated water clusters.\n\nA useful energetic picture is:\n\n\\[\n\\text{ionisation energy of H}\n\\quad\\text{balanced partly by}\\quad\n\\text{electron affinity + solvation/hydration energies}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n## 71.7 Hydrogen bonding — strength and special cases\n\nTypical hydrogen-bond energies are much smaller than normal covalent bonds, often roughly in the range:\n\n\\[\n4\\text{–}45\\ \\mathrm{kJ\\,mol^{-1}}\n\\]\n\nA common moderate hydrogen bond is of order \\(10\\ \\mathrm{kJ\\,mol^{-1}}\\).\n\nDespite being weak individually, hydrogen bonds strongly affect:\n\n- boiling point\n- melting point\n- viscosity\n- solubility\n- acidity\n- molecular association\n- crystal packing\n- biological structure\n\n### Strong symmetric/ionic hydrogen bonding\n\nA classic example is:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{[F-H-F]^-}\n\\]\n\nThis interaction is much stronger than an ordinary neutral dipole–dipole hydrogen bond.\n\n### Hydrogen bonding involving chloride\n\nChlorine usually forms weaker hydrogen bonds than F/O/N because of lower charge density, but suitable compounds can still show Cl-involved hydrogen bonding.\n\n### π-hydrogen bonding\n\nHydrogen may also interact with a π-electron cloud in suitable molecular geometries.\n\n---\n\n## 71.8 Hydrogen-bonding trends in hydrides\n\nWithout hydrogen bonding, boiling points in a group generally increase with increasing molar mass.\n\nImportant anomalies:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{H_2S < H_2Se < H_2Te \\ll H_2O}\n\\]\n\nWater boils dramatically higher than the trend predicted from H₂S, H₂Se and H₂Te.\n\nSimilarly:\n\n- HF is anomalously high compared with HCl/HBr/HI\n- NH₃ is anomalously high relative to PH₃/AsH₃/SbH₃\n\nThe reason is strong intermolecular hydrogen bonding.\n\n---\n\n## 71.9 Hydrogen bonding and acidity\n\nIntramolecular hydrogen bonding can either increase or decrease acidity depending on whether it stabilises the acid or the conjugate base.\n\n### o-Nitrophenol\n\nIntramolecular hydrogen bonding stabilises the undissociated molecule, so its acidity differs from meta/para analogues.\n\n### Maleic vs fumaric acid\n\nThe first conjugate base of maleic acid can be strongly stabilised by intramolecular hydrogen bonding.\n\nTherefore:\n\n- \\(K_{a1}\\) of maleic acid is greater than that of fumaric acid\n- \\(K_{a2}\\) of maleic acid is smaller because the monoanion is already stabilised and resists losing the second proton\n\n### Oxalic acid\n\nThe first conjugate base is stabilised relative to the dianion, contributing to:\n\n\\[\nK_{a1} \\gg K_{a2}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n## 71.10 Hydrogen bonding and physical properties of isomers\n\nOrtho isomers capable of intramolecular hydrogen bonding often remain less associated intermolecularly.\n\nConsequences may include:\n\n- lower boiling point\n- lower melting point\n- lower water solubility\n- greater volatility\n\nMeta and para isomers often form stronger intermolecular networks and may have higher melting/boiling points.\n\n---\n\n## 71.11 Extent of hydrogen bonding — number of sites matters\n\nThe extent of hydrogen bonding depends not only on bond strength but also on the number and orientation of donor/acceptor sites.\n\nExamples:\n\n### H₂O₂ vs H₂O\nH₂O₂ has more potential hydrogen-bonding sites per molecule than H₂O, allowing extensive association.\n\n### Ethanol vs glycerol\nGlycerol has three –OH groups and forms a much denser hydrogen-bond network than ethanol.\n\nHence glycerol is much more viscous.\n\n---\n\n## 71.12 Important preparation and use conditions of H₂\n\n### Haber process\nRepresentative industrial conditions:\n\n- about 380–450°C\n- high pressure, around 200 atm in classical descriptions\n- activated Fe catalyst\n\n### Methanol synthesis\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{CO + 2H_2 \\rightarrow CH_3OH}\n\\]\n\nClassical advanced texts describe Cu/Zn catalyst systems around elevated temperature.\n\n### Hydrogenation of oils\n\nUnsaturated fatty-acid chains:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{-CH=CH- + H_2 \\rightarrow -CH_2-CH_2-}\n\\]\n\nHydrogenation increases saturation and generally raises melting point.\n\nOther uses include:\n\n- nitrobenzene → aniline\n- benzene reduction in industrial organic synthesis\n- reduction of metal oxides\n- fuel and rocket applications\n\n---\n\n## 71.13 Five types of water in crystalline solids\n\nWater associated with crystals may occur as:\n\n1. **coordinated water** — directly bonded to a metal ion\n2. **hydrogen-bonded water** — outside the primary coordination sphere\n3. **lattice water** — occupies crystal-lattice positions\n4. **zeolitic water** — present in channels/cavities and often reversibly removable\n5. **clathrate water** — forms cage-like host frameworks around guest species\n\nA classic hydrate example is often represented as:\n\n\\[\n\\mathrm{[Cu(H_2O)_4]SO_4\\cdot H_2O}\n\\]\n\nshowing four coordinated water molecules and one additional lattice/hydrogen-bonded water molecule.\n\n---\n\n# 72. Final Integrated High-Yield Additions\n\nThe chapter should now also explicitly retain these advanced facts:\n\n- H₂ kinetic inertness is caused by high activation energy linked to strong H–H bonding.\n- Atomic hydrogen torch reaches roughly 4000 K; oxy-hydrogen flame is roughly 3000°C.\n- H₂/O₂ mixtures near 2:1 can be explosive.\n- Metallic hydrides can be variable-composition solid solutions and may cause embrittlement.\n- Ionic-hydride character is supported by molten electrolysis and H₂ evolution at the anode.\n- Hydrated proton stability is understood through large hydration energy.\n- Hydrogen-bond energies span a broad range and can include strong ionic cases such as \\([F-H-F]^-\\).\n- Hydrogen bonding can involve unusual donors/acceptors and even π systems.\n- Intramolecular hydrogen bonding can strongly alter acidity and boiling/melting behaviour.\n- The number of H-bonding sites explains viscosity/association differences such as ethanol vs glycerol.\n- Water in crystals may be coordinated, hydrogen-bonded, lattice, zeolitic or clathrate water.\n\n";
